Since Confluence stores pages in a hierarchy, sometimes I know _where_ a page is, but not exactly what it is named. Instead of searching, simply browsing the page hierarchy is the easiest way to find these pages when this is the case.

The confluence Move Page dialog includes a Browse view, alongside Advanced, Search, and Recently Viewed. The Insert/Edit Link dialog includes all of these plus some views for linking to attachments and the web, but it does *NOT* contain a browse view! This creates an inconsistent and disturbing UX: "Wait.. I could have SWORN there was a browse view on this dialog... Where is it!? Am I going insane!? What did I name that page? AAAAAAA" The user, in order to find the page, now has to open a *SECOND TAB* next to her editor window, to browse for the page and figure out what its title was, so she can then link to it by name in the editor.

Dialogs across the application that are used to select pages should have a consistent set of views for browsing, searching, and recent.

